<doc id="186475" wikidata="Q669094" url="?curid=186475" title="Arithmetical hierarchy">
<text>In mathematical logic, the arithmetical hierarchy, arithmetic hierarchy or Kleene–Mostowski hierarchy (after mathematicians Stephen Cole Kleene and Andrzej Mostowski) classifies certain sets based on the complexity of formulas that define them. Any set that receives a classification is called arithmetical. The arithmetical hierarchy was invented independently by Kleene (1943) and Mostowski (1946).

The arithmetical hierarchy is important in computability theory, effective descriptive set theory, and the study of formal theories such as Peano arithmetic.

The Tarski–Kuratowski algorithm provides an easy way to get an upper bound on the classifications assigned to a formula and the set it defines.

The hyperarithmetical hierarchy and the analytical hierarchy extend the arithmetical hierarchy to classify additional formulas and sets.

== The arithmetical hierarchy of formulas ==

The arithmetical hierarchy assigns classifications to the formulas in the language of first-order arithmetic. The classifications are denoted formula_1 and formula_2 for natural numbers &quot;n&quot; (including 0). The Greek letters here are lightface symbols, which indicates that the formulas do not contain 

If a formula formula_3 is logically equivalent to a formula having no unbounded quantifiers, i.e. in which all quantifiers are bounded quantifiers then formula_3 is assigned the classifications formula_5 and formula_6.

The classifications formula_1 and formula_2 are defined inductively for every natural number &quot;n&quot; using the following rules:
*If formula_3 is logically equivalent to a formula of the form formula_10, where formula_11 is formula_2, then formula_3 is assigned the classification formula_14.
*If formula_3 is logically equivalent to a formula of the form formula_16, where formula_11 is formula_1, then formula_3 is assigned the classification formula_20.

A formula_1 formula is equivalent to a formula that begins with some existential quantifiers and alternates formula_22 times between series of existential and universal quantifiers; while a formula_2 formula is equivalent to a formula that begins with some universal quantifiers and alternates analogously.

Because every first-order formula has a prenex normal form, every formula is assigned at least one classification. Because redundant quantifiers can be added to any formula, once a formula is assigned the classification formula_1 or formula_2 it will be assigned the classifications formula_26 and formula_27 for every &quot;m&quot; &gt; &quot;n&quot;. The only relevant classification assigned to a formula is thus the one with the least &quot;n&quot;; all the other classifications can be determined from it.

== The arithmetical hierarchy of sets of natural numbers ==

A set &quot;X&quot; of natural numbers is defined by a formula &quot;φ&quot; in the language of Peano arithmetic (the first-order language with symbols &quot;0&quot; for zero, &quot;S&quot; for the successor function, &quot;+&quot; for addition, &quot;×&quot; for multiplication, and &quot;=&quot; for equality), if the elements of &quot;X&quot; are exactly the numbers that satisfy &quot;φ&quot;. That is, for all natural numbers &quot;n&quot;,
:formula_28
where formula_29 is the numeral in the language of arithmetic corresponding to formula_30. A set is definable in first-order arithmetic if it is defined by some formula in the language of Peano arithmetic.

Each set &quot;X&quot; of natural numbers that is definable in first-order arithmetic is assigned classifications of the form formula_1, formula_2, and formula_33, where formula_30 is a natural number, as follows. If &quot;X&quot; is definable by a formula_1 formula then &quot;X&quot; is assigned the classification formula_1. If &quot;X&quot; is definable by a formula_2 formula then &quot;X&quot; is assigned the classification formula_2. If &quot;X&quot; is both formula_1 and formula_2 then formula_41 is assigned the additional classification formula_33.

Note that it rarely makes sense to speak of formula_33 formulas; the first quantifier of a formula is either existential or universal. So a formula_33 set is not necessarily defined by a formula_33 formula in the sense of a formula that is both formula_1 and formula_2; rather, there are both formula_1 and formula_2 formulas that define the set. For example, the set of odd natural numbers formula_30 is definable by either formula_51 or formula_52.

A parallel definition is used to define the arithmetical hierarchy on finite Cartesian powers of the set of natural numbers. Instead of formulas with one free variable, formulas with &quot;k&quot; free first-order variables are used to define the arithmetical hierarchy on sets of &quot;k&quot;-tuples of natural numbers. These are in fact related by the use of a pairing function.

== Meaning of the notation==

The following meanings can be attached to the notation for the arithmetical hierarchy on formulas.

The subscript formula_30 in the symbols formula_1 and formula_2 indicates the number of alternations of blocks of universal and existential first-order quantifiers that are used in a formula. Moreover, the outermost block is existential in formula_1 formulas and universal in formula_2 formulas.

The superscript formula_58 in the symbols formula_1, formula_2, and formula_33 indicates the type of the objects being quantified over. Type 0 objects are natural numbers, and objects of type formula_62 are functions that map the set of objects of type formula_63 to the natural numbers. Quantification over higher type objects, such as functions from natural numbers to natural numbers, is described by a superscript greater than 0, as in the analytical hierarchy. The superscript 0 indicates quantifiers over numbers, the superscript 1 would indicate quantification over functions from numbers to numbers (type 1 objects), the superscript 2 would correspond to quantification over functions that take a type 1 object and return a number, and so on.

== Examples ==

* The formula_64 sets of numbers are those definable by a formula of the form formula_65 where formula_11 has only bounded quantifiers. These are exactly the recursively enumerable sets.
* The set of natural numbers that are indices for Turing machines that compute total functions is formula_67. Intuitively, an index formula_68 falls into this set if and only if for every formula_69 &quot;there is an formula_70 such that the Turing machine with index formula_68 halts on input formula_69 after formula_70 steps&quot;. A complete proof would show that the property displayed in quotes in the previous sentence is definable in the language of Peano arithmetic by a formula_64 formula.
* Every formula_64 subset of Baire space or Cantor space is an open set in the usual topology on the space. Moreover, for any such set there is a computable enumeration of Gödel numbers of basic open sets whose union is the original set. For this reason, formula_64 sets are sometimes called &quot;effectively open&quot;. Similarly, every formula_77 set is closed and the formula_77 sets are sometimes called &quot;effectively closed&quot;.
* Every arithmetical subset of Cantor space or Baire space is a Borel set. The lightface Borel hierarchy extends the arithmetical hierarchy to include additional Borel sets. For example, every formula_67 subset of Cantor or Baire space is a formula_80 set, that is, a set that equals the intersection of countably many open sets. Moreover, each of these open sets is formula_64 and the list of Gödel numbers of these open sets has a computable enumeration. If formula_82 is a formula_5 formula with a free set variable formula_41 and free number variables formula_85 then the formula_67 set formula_87 is the intersection of the formula_64 sets of the form formula_89 as formula_30 ranges over the set of natural numbers.
* The formula_91 formulas can be checked by going over all cases one by one, which is possible because all their quantifiers are bounded. The time for this is polynomial in their arguments (e.g. polynomial in formula_30 for formula_93); thus their corresponding decision problems are included in E (as formula_30 is exponential in its number of bits). This no longer holds under alternative definitions of formula_91 that allow the use of primitive recursive functions, as now the quantifiers may be bounded by any primitive recursive function of the arguments.
* The formula_91 formulas under an alternative definition, that allows the use of primitive recursive functions with bounded quantifiers, correspond to sets of natural numbers of the form formula_97 for a primitive recursive function formula_98. This is because allowing bounded quantifier adds nothing to the definition: for a primitive recursive formula_98, formula_100 is the same as formula_101, and formula_102 is the same as formula_103; with course-of-values recursion each of these can be defined by a single primitive recursive function.

== Relativized arithmetical hierarchies ==

Just as we can define what it means for a set &quot;X&quot; to be recursive relative to another set &quot;Y&quot; by allowing the computation defining &quot;X&quot; to consult &quot;Y&quot; as an oracle we can extend this notion to the whole arithmetic hierarchy and define what it means for &quot;X&quot; to be formula_1, formula_33 or formula_2 in &quot;Y&quot;, denoted respectively formula_107, formula_108 and formula_109. To do so, fix a set of natural numbers &quot;Y&quot; and add a predicate for membership of &quot;Y&quot; to the language of Peano arithmetic. We then say that &quot;X&quot; is in formula_107 if it is defined by a formula_1 formula in this expanded language. In other words, &quot;X&quot; is formula_107 if it is defined by a formula_113 formula allowed to ask questions about membership of &quot;Y&quot;. Alternatively one can view the formula_107 sets as those sets that can be built starting with sets recursive in &quot;Y&quot; and alternately taking unions and intersections of these sets up to &quot;n&quot; times.

For example, let &quot;Y&quot; be a set of natural numbers. Let &quot;X&quot; be the set of numbers divisible by an element of &quot;Y&quot;. Then &quot;X&quot; is defined by the formula formula_115 so &quot;X&quot; is in formula_116 (actually it is in formula_117 as well, since we could bound both quantifiers by &quot;n&quot;).

== Arithmetic reducibility and degrees ==

Arithmetical reducibility is an intermediate notion between Turing reducibility and hyperarithmetic reducibility.

A set is arithmetical (also arithmetic and arithmetically definable) if it is defined by some formula in the language of Peano arithmetic. Equivalently &quot;X&quot; is arithmetical if &quot;X&quot; is formula_1 or formula_2 for some natural number &quot;n&quot;. A set &quot;X&quot; is arithmetical in a set &quot;Y&quot;, denoted formula_120, if &quot;X&quot; is definable as some formula in the language of Peano arithmetic extended by a predicate for membership of &quot;Y&quot;. Equivalently, &quot;X&quot; is arithmetical in &quot;Y&quot; if &quot;X&quot; is in formula_107 or formula_109 for some natural number &quot;n&quot;. A synonym for formula_120 is: &quot;X&quot; is arithmetically reducible to &quot;Y&quot;.

The relation formula_120 is reflexive and transitive, and thus the relation formula_125 defined by the rule

:formula_126
is an equivalence relation. The equivalence classes of this relation are called the arithmetic degrees; they are partially ordered under formula_127.

==The arithmetical hierarchy of subsets of Cantor and Baire space==

The Cantor space, denoted formula_128, is the set of all infinite sequences of 0s and 1s; the Baire space, denoted formula_129 or formula_130, is the set of all infinite sequences of natural numbers. Note that elements of the Cantor space can be identified with sets of natural numbers and elements of the Baire space with functions from natural numbers to natural numbers.

The ordinary axiomatization of second-order arithmetic uses a set-based language in which the set quantifiers can naturally be viewed as quantifying over Cantor space. A subset of Cantor space is assigned the classification formula_1 if it is definable by a formula_1 formula. The set is assigned the classification formula_2 if it is definable by a formula_2 formula. If the set is both formula_1 and formula_2 then it is given the additional classification formula_33. For example, let formula_138 be the set of all infinite binary strings that aren&#x27;t all 0 (or equivalently the set of all non-empty sets of natural numbers). As formula_139 we see that formula_140 is defined by a formula_64 formula and hence is a formula_64 set.

Note that while both the elements of the Cantor space (regarded as sets of natural numbers) and subsets of the Cantor space are classified in arithmetic hierarchies, these are not the same hierarchy. In fact the relationship between the two hierarchies is interesting and non-trivial. For instance the formula_2 elements of the Cantor space are not (in general) the same as the elements formula_41 of the Cantor space so that formula_145 is a formula_2 subset of the Cantor space. However, many interesting results relate the two hierarchies.

There are two ways that a subset of Baire space can be classified in the arithmetical hierarchy.
*A subset of Baire space has a corresponding subset of Cantor space under the map that takes each function from formula_147 to formula_147 to the characteristic function of its graph. A subset of Baire space is given the classification formula_1, formula_2, or formula_33 if and only if the corresponding subset of Cantor space has the same classification.
*An equivalent definition of the arithmetical hierarchy on Baire space is given by defining the arithmetical hierarchy of formulas using a functional version of second-order arithmetic; then the arithmetical hierarchy on subsets of Cantor space can be defined from the hierarchy on Baire space. This alternate definition gives exactly the same classifications as the first definition.

A parallel definition is used to define the arithmetical hierarchy on finite Cartesian powers of Baire space or Cantor space, using formulas with several free variables. The arithmetical hierarchy can be defined on any effective Polish space; the definition is particularly simple for Cantor space and Baire space because they fit with the language of ordinary second-order arithmetic.

Note that we can also define the arithmetic hierarchy of subsets of the Cantor and Baire spaces relative to some set of natural numbers. In fact boldface formula_152 is just the union of formula_107 for all sets of natural numbers &quot;Y&quot;. Note that the boldface hierarchy is just the standard hierarchy of Borel sets.

== Extensions and variations==

It is possible to define the arithmetical hierarchy of formulas using a language extended with a function symbol for each primitive recursive function. This variation slightly changes the classification of formula_91, since using primitive recursive functions in first-order Peano arithmetic requires, in general, an unbounded existential quantifier, and thus some sets that are in formula_5 by this definition are strictly in formula_64 by the definition given in the beginning of this article. The class formula_64 and thus all higher classes in the hierarchy remain unaffected.

A more semantic variation of the hierarchy can be defined on all finitary relations on the natural numbers; the following definition is used. Every computable relation is defined to be formula_91. The classifications formula_1 and formula_2 are defined inductively with the following rules.
* If the relation formula_161 is formula_1 then the relation formula_163 is defined to be formula_20
* If the relation formula_161 is formula_2 then the relation formula_167 is defined to be formula_14
This variation slightly changes the classification of some sets. In particular, formula_91, as a class of sets (definable by the relations in the class), is identical to formula_170 as the latter was formerly defined. It can be extended to cover finitary relations on the natural numbers, Baire space, and Cantor space.

== Properties ==

The following properties hold for the arithmetical hierarchy of sets of natural numbers and the arithmetical hierarchy of subsets of Cantor or Baire space.

* The collections formula_2 and formula_1 are closed under finite unions and finite intersections of their respective elements.
* A set is formula_1 if and only if its complement is formula_2. A set is formula_33 if and only if the set is both formula_1 and formula_2, in which case its complement will also be formula_33.
* The inclusions formula_179 and formula_180 hold for all formula_30. Thus the hierarchy does not collapse. This is a direct consequence of Post&#x27;s theorem.
* The inclusions formula_182, formula_183 and formula_184 hold for formula_185.
:*For example, for a universal Turing machine &quot;T&quot;, the set of pairs (&quot;n&quot;,&quot;m&quot;) such that &quot;T&quot; halts on &quot;n&quot; but not on &quot;m&quot;, is in formula_186 (being computable with an oracle to the halting problem) but not in formula_187.
:*formula_188. The inclusion is strict by the definition given in this article, but an identity with formula_170 holds under one of the variations of the definition given above.

== Relation to Turing machines ==
===Computable sets===
If &quot;S&quot; is a Turing computable set, then both &quot;S&quot; and its complement are recursively enumerable (if &quot;T&quot; is a Turing machine giving 1 for inputs in &quot;S&quot; and 0 otherwise, we may build a Turing machine halting only on the former, and another halting only on the latter).

By Post&#x27;s theorem, both &quot;S&quot; and its complement are in formula_64. This means that &quot;S&quot; is both in formula_64 and in formula_77, and hence it is in formula_170.

Similarly, for every set &quot;S&quot; in formula_170, both &quot;S&quot; and its complement are in formula_64 and are therefore (by Post&#x27;s theorem) recursively enumerable by some Turing machines &quot;T&quot;1 and &quot;T&quot;2, respectively. For every number &quot;n&quot;, exactly one of these halts. We may therefore construct a Turing machine &quot;T&quot; that alternates between &quot;T&quot;1 and &quot;T&quot;2, halting and returning 1 when the former halts or halting and returning 0 when the latter halts. Thus &quot;T&quot; halts on every &quot;n&quot; and returns whether it is in &quot;S&quot;; so &quot;S&quot; is computable.

===Summary of main results===
The Turing computable sets of natural numbers are exactly the sets at level formula_170 of the arithmetical hierarchy. The recursively enumerable sets are exactly the sets at level formula_64.

No oracle machine is capable of solving its own halting problem (a variation of Turing&#x27;s proof applies). The halting problem for a formula_108 oracle in fact sits in formula_199.

Post&#x27;s theorem establishes a close connection between the arithmetical hierarchy of sets of natural numbers and the Turing degrees. In particular, it establishes the following facts for all &quot;n&quot; ≥ 1:
* The set formula_200 (the &quot;n&quot;th Turing jump of the empty set) is many-one complete in formula_1.
* The set formula_202 is many-one complete in formula_2.
* The set formula_204 is Turing complete in formula_33.

The polynomial hierarchy is a &quot;feasible resource-bounded&quot; version of the arithmetical hierarchy in which polynomial length bounds are placed on the numbers involved (or, equivalently, polynomial time bounds are placed on the Turing machines involved). It gives a finer classification of some sets of natural numbers that are at level formula_170 of the arithmetical hierarchy.

